{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605312"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15866"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15866"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.17,0.13,0.08,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114662"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8557"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96665"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8680"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20529"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114662"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe paramesonephric (M\u00fcllerian) ducts are paired embryological structures that contribute to reproductive tract development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures develops from the paramesonephric ducts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fallopian tubes","Lower third of vagina","Ovaries","Round ligaments","Broad ligaments"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efallopian tubes\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the unfused cranial portions of the paramesonephric (M\u00fcllerian) ducts. The middle portions of these ducts fuse to form the uterus and cervix, while the caudal portions contribute to the upper two-thirds of the vagina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elower third of vagina\u003C/strong\u003E develops from the urogenital sinus, whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Eovaries\u003C/strong\u003E develop from gonadal ridges. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eround ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E develop from gubernaculum and the \u003Cstrong\u003Ebroad ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E develop from peritoneal folds. In male embryos, anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone produced by Sertoli cells causes regression of the paramesonephric ducts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paramesonephric (M\u00fcllerian) ducts develop into female reproductive structures including fallopian tubes, uterus, and upper vagina.","Lower vagina develops from the urogenital sinus, not from the M\u00fcllerian ducts.","Anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone causes regression of paramesonephric ducts in male development."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015","Rey R, Josso N, Racine C. Sexual Differentiation. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc. [Updated 2020 May 27]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279001/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15866"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T14:52:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T15:18:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","